\'b6 39. I cannot say that my frame of mind towards the work of others is much different. For example, after reading the reflections of a certain well-respected figure four or five days ago, I tried thinking about his works. His aim is to conform to the "facts." And he actually has the "facts." However, they are no more than shallow and tepid facts. That said, he knows about many systems of thought and the words for displaying deeper facts. By thinking he pulls them towards his own shallow facts, and in appearance he comes to raise himself to the level of those thoughts. As a result, he describes and discusses things he does not know about. He tosses around deep language lightly. He expresses shallow facts as if they were deep. He acts as though he had solved the problem as soon as he arrives at its gate. He does not know the first thing about what he is doing. He is a supporter of the principle of rejecting falsehood, but to radicalize his shallow experiences, he ought to have just expressed them in their shallowness. He should have discarded all his borrowings and tried to think in conformity with his own vision.---As I was thinking this, two words from his reflections surfaced in my mind as proof of my own criticism. Talking about the "radical," he claims the person who speaks about it is, surprisingly, a non-radical, and it is rather the one who does not speak of it who is radical. This is a fact. It is such a well-known fact that we don't question it. And yet, he takes these words to be a refutation of those who would explain the radical. From this it is clear that he has never questioned the "radical," since his attitude reveals not even a whit of sympathy or compassion towards the sufferings and strivings of those who demand the radical. There are a variety of frames of mind among those people who demand the radical in places that cannot be made exhaustively radical. How could it be that those who do not see this are the ones with the authority to discuss the "radical"? He no doubt presents himself as a "radical person," but his sort of radicalness is surely no more than a congealed way of seeing and dealing with things or the idleness of an ignorant compromise, unconscious of its contradiction.---He also mocks the desire for possessions and says that even in his own household's experience, possession is impossible. This also shows that he lacks a desire for possessions and so is incapable of understanding the desire for possession. How could one who is (or was) truly burning with a desire for possessions say definitively that it is impossible? He may be of a frame of mind to mutter that there is (or was) no such power in himself, but even if this were a basis from which to mock oneself, it could not become a basis from which to mock others. Surely, he was drawing from his own shallow and tepid experience to arrogantly criticize a world he knows nothing about. \'85\'85\
