\'b6 42. Behind the biting sarcasm that Shaw showers on society, he burns with idealistic zeal and righteous indignation. Yet, there are almost no moving moments in his works. He is unable to sketch human beings touched by love or suffering on the path. *In extremis*, he is even unable to sketch out mankind's form. In him, there is no pity, just a heart that hates evil. This connection is shown by his Mephisto. His Mephisto only directs its arrows of negativity at the hypocrite---at worldly passion which disguises its stench. He is pleased by destruction but never seeks to destroy what is truly beautiful or good. He is, so to speak, a Mephisto who has been exchanged for a knight of justice. Thus, this Mephisto does not have a Faust, and in Shaw himself there is seemingly no sign of one either. He is settled and unmoving like a lump of goodness, or one who constructed himself. He appears to be one who does not proceed on the painful path of forging himself but receives strength and self-confidence from social salvation. On the authority of his idealistic zeal and righteous indignation he is without any hesitation in boldly concentrating his heaps of abuse upon society's hypocrisies and non-radical points.\
